what is cloud watch?

is a monitoring tool it collects and tracks metrics, logs, and events from your AWS resources and applications.

A typical CloudWatch dashboard might show:

CPU usage of your EC2 servers
Number of Lambda invocations
Error rates and latency
Log insights queries
Alarm statuses

by default when we create ec2 instance cloud watch is enabled?

Basic Monitoring (Free) — Enabled by Default ✅
When you create an EC2 instance, Basic Monitoring is automatically enabled for free.
It collects metrics like:

CPU Utilization
Network In/Out
Disk Read/Write
Status Check Failed

❌ Not collected by default (even with Basic Monitoring):

Memory Usage (RAM)  — AWS can't see inside your OS
Disk Space          — AWS can't see inside your OS
Running Processes   — AWS can't see inside your OS

To collect these, you need to install the CloudWatch Agent manually inside your EC2 instance.

how to set 80 percent CPU we should get notification in watch cloud?


Step-by-Step Guide

Step 1 — Open CloudWatch

Go to AWS Console
Search for CloudWatch
Click on Alarms → All Alarms
Click Create Alarm


Step 2 — Select Metric

Click Select Metric
Choose EC2 → Per-Instance Metrics
Search for your Instance ID
Select CPUUtilization
Click Select Metric


Step 3 — Set the Threshold (80%)

Statistic → Average
Period → 5 minutes
Threshold type → Static
Condition → Greater than or equal to
Value → 80


This means → "Alert me when CPU is >= 80% for 5 minutes"


Step 4 — Set Notification (SNS)

Under Notification section
Select In alarm state
Choose an existing SNS topic OR create a new one and create subscription and select email
Enter your email address
AWS will send a confirmation email — you must click confirm ✅


Step 5 — Name the Alarm

Give it a name like EC2-CPU-High-Alert
Add a description (optional)
Click Create Alarm

